@dcgoss I just went down a similar path as you the last two days. It took a lot of hunting around for a decent django storage backend that supports GCS before I stumbled upon the `gs.py` implementation here. Unfortunately, it uses the S3 interop mode instead of Google's GCP Python library...

I should note that I came across a [decent implementation here](https://github.com/BradWhittington/django-gcloud-storage/blob/412fe79c71c0567f33d6cb442c88b222826c5efe/django_gcloud_storage/__init__.py), but it doesn't seem to be actively developed and I'd prefer to use something living in this project instead.

Anyways, you would be interested in the conversation over at PR #236. Basically, the current `gs.py` implementation uses GCS's S3 interop mode which is not meant for production or long term use. It looks like that PR is close to merging... I'm eagerly waiting :)

@jirikuncar about the spaces, it's the way we're supposed to write in French, see https://www.thoughtco.com/how-to-use-french-punctuation-4086509

> In French, a space is required both before and after all two- (or more) part punctuation marks and symbols, including : ; « » ! ? % $ #

I will add the missing dot.

I know your tool is based on openpyxl - I see there is good support for different formats: https://openpyxl.readthedocs.io/en/default/styles.html - but it might be possible to provide wrappers around this e.g. pass in a dictionary with styles to format single, or ranges of rows or columns for a given sheet e.g. as crude JSON:
```
{
	"styles": [{
		"sheet_name": "One",
		"formats": {
			"rows": [{
				"start": 0,
				"end": 2,
				"height": 2.0,
				"foreground": "red",
				"background": "blue",
				"pattern": "diagonal"
				},
				{
				"start": 3,
				"height": 3.0,
				"foreground": "blue",
				"pattern": "vertical",
				"font-weight": "italics"
			}
			],
			"cols": [{
				"start": 3,
				"width": 3.0,
				"font-color": "red",
				"font-weight": "bold",
				"font-size": 16
			}]
		}
	}]
}
```
(`end` is optional; if omitted, just apply to a single row/column)

One could get even fancier and allow formatting of individual cells (for example; it  might be the one containing the Grand Total).

May also be useful to define a base style that applies to the whole sheet e.g. the default font name and size, or default row height.

