@vitaly-krugl Understood, however, I draw a different conclusion.  I think the `2to3` conversion tool is doing the right thing assuming your intention is to A) switch to python 3 and B) preserve existing behavior.  Left to its own devices, yes, the modified code in Python 2.7 would be slower than the original in Python 2.7, but it would be on par with Python 3.x.  In most cases, the original code could be rewritten (or have been written from the start) such that generators and iterators are used in 2.7, and then when translated to 3, also use generators and iterators.  It's only a degradation because we're already using the slow version before the conversion AND staying in 2.x AFTER the conversion, and not necessarily the fault of the tool

Meanwhile, [2to3](https://docs.python.org/2/library/2to3.html) has some options for disabling some of the fixers.  For example, if we add `from future_builtins import zip`, then the `dict(zip(self.getFieldNames(), values))` example would not apply.  There are also lots of missed opportunities to use [six](http://pythonhosted.org/six/#module-six.moves).

Ultimately, I think the exercise was a success in that despite the large and storied code base, a translation is possible with minimal effort.  Right now, I'm interested in knowing whether or not these changes break existing 2.7 installations.  So far, I can only use my own anecdotal experience and tests, but I know that's not 100% coverage.  I'm hoping someone else will try it out and help expose holes in test coverage.

