Be aware that compiling:
```
    function to_hook(uint x) returns (uint) {
      return x;
    }
    function f(uint x) returns (uint) {
        return to_hook(x);
    }
```
May not result in the excepted behavior.

I think that, at the EVM level, `to_hook` is actually duplicated, and there is no jump from `f` to the 'original' `to_hook`.

So if you want to generate a hook for every transaction reaching `to_hook`, you have two create two hooks (one at the beginning of `to_hook`, one inside `f`)

