The main way that jupyter does multiple outputs is with [`display_data` messages](http://jupyter-client.readthedocs.io/en/latest/messaging.html#display-data). Roughly, they look like this:

```
display_data.content: {
  data: {
    'text/html': '<b>hey</b>'
  }
}

display_data.content: {
  data: {
    'text/html': '<b>woo</b>'
  }
}
```

Recently, [`update_display_data` was added](http://jupyter-client.readthedocs.io/en/latest/messaging.html#update-display-data) which allows for updating prior displays by way of a `display_id` inside the `transient` field:

```
display_data.content: {
  data: {
    'text/html': '<b>hey</b>'
  },
  transient: {
    'display_id': '1234'
  }
}

update_display_data.content: {
  data: {
    'text/html': '<b>HEY</b>'
  },
  transient: {
    'display_id': '1234'
  }
}
```

It seems like a TensorFlow summary object could end up as a mimetype here rather than going out on the `stream` interface, which lets you emit to same parent message (which goes to a cell in nteract & jupyter notebook).

/cc @craigcitro for thoughts on `stream` messages

