In master. Sorry for not being clear, I meant `==` in the definition of `__next__` inside make_iterator:
```
.def("__next__", [](state &s) -> ValueType {
                if (!s.first)
                    ++s.it;
                else
                    s.first = false;
                if (s.it == s.end)
                    throw stop_iteration();
                return *s.it;
            }
```
and the fact that the range-based `for` in C++ uses `!=`:
```
    auto && __range = range_expression ;
    for (auto __begin = begin_expr, __end = end_expr;
            __begin != __end; ++__begin) {
```
So an iterator written with only C++ `for` in mind could be missing `==` and may not work as argument to make_iterator().
It's not really important and and I don't mind if this issue is just closed.

